data.content:
# EF Core 10 Breaking Changes for Your Code

## 1. `SetProperty` – value overload removed

EF Core 10 removed the `SetProperty(Expression<Func<T,P>>, P value)` overload. Only the two-lambda overload remains: `SetProperty(Expression<Func<T,P>>, Expression<Func<T,P>>)`.

Your `Expression.Constant("foo")` no longer matches any overload. Wrap it in a lambda:

```csharp
var sParameter = Expression.Parameter(typeof(SetPropertyCalls<Blog>), "s");
var blogParameter = Expression.Parameter(typeof(Blog), "b");

// Build: s => s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, b => "foo")
var valueLambda = Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(
    Expression.Constant("foo"), blogParameter);

setters = Expression.Lambda<Func<SetPropertyCalls<Blog>, SetPropertyCalls<Blog>>>(
    Expression.Call(
        instance: setters.Body,
        methodName: nameof(SetPropertyCalls<Blog>.SetProperty),
        typeArguments: new[] { typeof(string) },
        arguments: new Expression[]
        {
            Expression.Lambda<Func<Blog, string>>(
                Expression.Property(blogParameter, nameof(Blog.Name)), blogParameter),
            valueLambda   // was: Expression.Constant("foo")
        }),
    setters.Parameters);
```

## 2. Complex types – default column naming now includes prefix

EF Core 10 prefixes complex-property columns with the property name to avoid collisions. `ShippingAddress.Street` → column `ShippingAddress_Street`, `BillingAddress.Street` → `BillingAddress_Street`.

If you need to preserve existing schema (no new migration), configure columns explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street");   // old column name
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingStreet");
    });
});

// For nested: Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, pb =>
    {
        pb.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            sa.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("Payment_BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

Or, if starting fresh, just add a new migration and update the database—the new defaults avoid ambiguity automatically.

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` – `CommandSource` parameter added

EF Core 10 adds a `CommandSource commandSource` parameter to the diagnostic methods:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        CommandSource commandSource)   // ← new parameter
    { /* logging */ }
}
```

`CommandSource` is an enum (`CommandSource.LinqQuery`, `CommandSource.Migrations`, `CommandSource.ExecuteUpdate`, etc.) indicating what triggered the command—useful for filtering your logs.

---

**Summary of fixes:**

| Area | What broke | Fix |
|------|-----------|-----|
| `SetProperty` | Value-constant overload removed | Wrap value in `Expression.Lambda` |
| Complex types | Column names now prefixed | Add explicit `HasColumnName()` or re-migrate |
| Diagnostics logger | New `CommandSource` param | Add parameter to implementation |
